title: While liquid, kills fleas; easy on skin
text:
Somebody out here in SiVal must've gene-spliced a super-flea last summer. All the usual topicals (Advantage, fFontline) just quit working; I was desperate and sampled a number of different over-the-counter products. This was the best of the sprays.

The clove-and-peppermint formulation did kill fleas on contact WHILE IT WAS WET. I had to give the little mustards a good soaking – not just a gentle misting –and it toil a minute or two for them to die,die.DIE!!. After it dried, it didn't seem to do much. These were the two most effective techniques:

1. We sprayed it on the floor in front of us and then walked through it from place to place.

2. We sprayed our arms and legs when the fleas jumped on us. I had tried the clove-peppermint wipes (after I found out all the cats objected strongly to the smell, I figured somebody should use them) but they dried out my skin. This didn't. It was at least as effective as bug repellent made for humans, and I wasn't worried to use around the kittens.

Comfortis was what finally got rid of the fleas. I'd never heard of it before my vet told me. You need a prescription and it costs a bomb – even more if you want it to ship in less than two long, itchy weeks. But what price sanity?

text:
What to say....
This isn't something you will forget easily if its on the highest of 3 settings from a Human perspective but its not Horrible either. Lol! I removed it form the cardboard box(not pictured) but it will lay pretty nicely on a counter top even when not in use you can simply roll it up without much of a problem. Mine was wrinkled from folding and not rolling it up.

I am a vine reviewer just to let everyone know that I am given the opportunity to request products on Amazon to test out under normal circumstances for my private use at home to see if they are worth buying or not. This is just my 2 cents worth to help typical buyers online get a different perspective other than the general advertisement which can sometimes be taken as misleading.

Pros
Mat proportions and measurements are accurate though not pictured at this time
The meter has 3 static settings on the lcd screen
Comes with a 9V battery
User can add sound that will beep when the mat is activated from a pet or human touching it in any way
Has a sturdy battery door that will lock into place on both ends to stay put
Comes with a paper manual and printed instructions on the outside of the box
Works as intended without harming a living creature that is caught unaware while being used as a correction tool on a flat surface
Completely portable without sticky residue behind since its plastic in nature with embedded wiring in the mat avoiding safety issues

Cons
none, other than having a rechargeable option would be nice

Thank you for your time and please consider giving me an upvote if you find my review helpful while making a more informed buying decision.

title: New Pup Parents behold, a cave fit for the wolf’s descendants!
text:
We recently got a corgi one week ago. We’ve both had dogs of varying sizes but never as a puppy. This was a new challenge and we’ve learned through trial and error what’s worked best. And best so far has been her crate!

We had a bed and an open space before for her. She elected to chew the pillow and preferred the smallest corner where we had our vacuum robot.

She has responded well to crating (fortunately).

In regard to the set up, it was relatively straight forward as it pops/opens up when you pull it. Be careful with your fingers as they may get trapped between the walls of the cage as you open it up.

The doors to the crate have different resistances, unsure for what reason but not an issue. Very happy to have the divider included as it allowed us to make the crate a more appropriate size for her.

We connected her crate to a play pen and it’s worked as an adjunct play/eating/stooling area for her when she’s not out and about in the apartment.

title: I enjoy the peace of mind Furbo is able to provide for me!
text:
I received my Furbo 2 years ago as a gift. I have 4 dogs and live in a townhouse, so I was concerned about barking while away. It did take me about 30 mins to set up , but once that was done , it’s been no problem.
Overall , I’m very pleased with it. I’ve come to rely on it to notify when the dogs are active or barking. They quickly learned to come running for treat tosses. I’ve had no problem finding treats that work.
A big plus for me is I receive notifications when a person is spotted. The Furbo is located in a spot that notifies me if someone enters the two main entrances. Not only do I enjoy checking on the dogs , but always know when someone has entered my home. If I’m upstairs, I can see what’s going on or communicate with my husband. All and all , after 2 yrs. I am very happy and checking Furbo multiple times a day. I’ve not had any issues and the person notification has been a big plus. Best gift ever !

title: Keeps my cat from scratching the door
text: Lifesaver! My cat does not like to sleep through the night; rather, she likes to wake me up and then ignore me when I'm awake (what a brat). I started locking her outside of my bedroom at night, but she'd start scratching at the door at 4am until I came out, and then she'd promptly ignore me! In attempts to get sleep, I tried ignoring her (the scratching became more vigorous), yelling at her (the scratching became more vigorous), spraying her with water (the scratching became more vigorous), and just letting her in the room (she'd lick my face until I woke up). Clearly, the lesson learned is that my cat enjoys making me feel miserable. This SSScat changed that. I set it up in front of my closed door, and the first night I heard her come to the door to scratch, a "SSSS" sound, and a high-pitched "MRAWWWW" and jump. Since then, there has been no scratching of the door. I don't even think I would need to turn the thing on; my cat is horrified of the device when she sees me take it out, and when she sees it she stays a foot away and never takes her eyes off of it. I now sleep soundly, and give my cat the attention she wants during normal hours.

title: My dogs like everything, including cat toys
text:
As someone who is owned by cats, I am constantly looking for toys to entertain and amuse my furry kids. My dogs like everything, including cat toys, but the cats are harder to shop for. They usually prefer the box. I liked this cat toy.

The box includes one small light up ball, and six easy to snap together pieces. The ball was lit for about a week, and then stopped lighting. There is no on/off switch on the ball, if there was it probably would affect it's ability to roll smoothly. There are 4 curved pieces of track so that you can make a circle, and two small end pieces so that you could opt to make a wavy line instead. There are openings on the top portion of the pieces so that a cat can bat at the ball while it moves along the track.

If I give the ball a tap in the track it spins around in a circle 2 or 3 times. One of my cats is mildly entertained for a minute or two by this toy, but he really enjoys literally sitting in the middle of the circle it forms. He seems to think it makes a good throne for him. When I formed it into a wavy line it did not appeal to him at all.

As for the box, my cats could probably curl up in one at a time it if it were a top opening box, but this is a side opening box. If you are a cat person, you will understand what I mean by this.

title: Keeps Kittens Fuller Longer
text:
I thought I was being careful with my first choice of dry kitten food for my 2 kittens. However, I noticed that even after eating their apportioned amount, they seemed to be starving shortly thereafter, as though I had fed them nothing at all. So I would feed them more, and they began to get overweight.

For the sake of their health, I had to find a cat food that would fill them up without overfeeding. I went seeking a product with a more substantial set of ingredients and I found Organix. What a hearty list of ingredients! Free-range chickens! These kittens would be eating better than I do! I was worried by some of the reviews that said their cats did not enjoy the flavor, but I thought I'd give it a shot.

Great news! My kittens love the taste. And they seem to stay fuller longer - they don't cry for food nearly as much as they used to. I'm limiting them to their proper amount and I hope to see a return to a healthy weight soon. I'm so glad to find an affordable organic option with Amazon's Subscribe & Save.

title: Great Cold Weather Option
text: Great option for cold weather.  Nothing is worse than frozen water in the winter.  This waterer solves this problem.  Works below 0 F.  The main conern I have seen in the reviews and experienced myself was the heater seperating from the bottle.  The solution I found was to keep the waterer pretty full to prevent the top section from overheating.  (Basically the element has no place to send the heat if the water does not touch it, overheats, and seperates from the bottle.)  Farm Innovators did replace this under warranty for me but the issue can be avoided. I recommend keeping this full enough to have water in contact with the black heater to avoid the problem.  Hope this helps!

title: Best impulse purchase I’ve made!
text: I bought this camera thinking it would just be something fun to have to see what my dog does while I’m away. Little did I know it would help in a dog medical emergency!  While i was away, my dog somehow got into her medication and ate a weeks worth of pills. When I got home I saw the house was covered in vomit and something was obviously wrong with her. I was able to check the Furbo recordings and see what time she had eaten all of her pills. This information helped greatly when I had to call animal poison control and go to the emergency vet!  So thankful for this camera!  I will be keeping the activity alerts on from now on. Had I had this option turned on, i could have caught her in the act and prevented her from eating too many pills. Thank you Furbo!

title: Look Closely - It's Misleading
text:
I am bothered with the fact that the pictures on the page for this sweet potato product gives the impression the first ingredient is chicken. It is not. It is corn. The third is sweet potato. I also see this was made in China.

The chicken flavor package lists this as the ingredients: Corn, Chicken, Sorbitol (a sweetener), Fructose (a sweetener), Pork Gelatin, Barley Malt Syrup (a sweetener), Maltodextrin (a sweetener mostly), SWEET POTATOES....and then a whole bunch of other stuff I can't pronounce and got tired of searching what they were for..

I signed on to purchase more SmartBones products. But if the seller sees a reason to pretend the first ingredient is an animal protein, the company must not trust its own product enough to be upfront about it. Change the picture.

title: Quality high density foam dog beds
text: So there are a few very important things you need to know when buying this product. First as you can see in the photos I posted that the measurements are a bit less than advertised. I let the beds sit out (I bought one for each of my Belgian Malinois) for 3 days to allow them to properly expand since they come vacuum sealed. So I think the company should adjust the measurements listed. Now there is another and extremely IMPORTANT reason why I let these dog beds sit outside (with all the covers off) for 3 days. The chemical smell from the fire retardant to meet shipping codes  is so awful and strong. The package says to let air out for 6 to 10 hours before use. This recommendation needs to be changed! Remember a canine's sense of smell is stronger than ours and it took 72 hours of these sitting outside for me to nolonger smell that chemical smell. Foam bedding for humans or pets, is only safe to use when oder is no longer present. So be a good dog owner and don't put your dog on this bed while its still stinky! Also wash the covers before you let your dog lay on it because the covers have the same smell. After all that, these make incredible dog beds! They are huge which I love and they appear to be a high density foam because neither I or my dogs sink when laying on it. My dogs definitely love these beds more than any other and lay on them and wrestle on them all the time. Its nice that they have a comfortable place on the wood floors. I shopped around for a while before I picked them because my dogs deserve the best. I think the cost is reasonable since these dog beds will actually last for years. title: LOVE Armarkat cat trees!!!
text: I have tried other cat trees brands and none in the price range ever compare with the quality of Armarkat. I have three Armarkat trees that are 7 years old and are doing just fine despite multi-cat use (abuse, lol). I just got two of this tree, they each took maybe 10 minutes to put together and they are awesome. The only thing they don't come with is something to cover the bolt heads on the bottom to protect your wooden floor. I used the thin felt for the bottoms of chairs and table legs, simple. I greatly prefer the fleece covering to a carpet covering for a couple of reasons: their claws cannot get stuck in the felt, it is simple to brush hair off of it and if a hairball gets upchucked on it it is extremely simple to clean. Armarkat creates very cat-friendly designs too, other companies will make trees that require the cat to climb straight up and then have to jump all the way down from the top even if it's a 6 ft. tree. That's dangerous for the cat. Armarkat trees always give the cat a safe way up and down so he can have fun without falling 6 feet to the floor. I love Armarkat cat trees!

title: JERRY-RIGGED IT TO WORK WITHOUT VELCRO OR SCREWS . . .
text:
. . . at least during the winter when I have no intention of opening that window. (Have no idea what I'm going to do once summer comes around. Perhaps I'll leave that window closed & open one of the other windows in that room instead). Have not figured out how to load a photo of what I did, so here it is in written form. Hope you can understand what I'm saying:

On each of the two legs - I secured one end of a flat shoe lace to top-most section of leg closest to wall, with a ping-pong size wiffle ball tied to the other end of the shoe lace. Held cat bed against wall, draped shoe laces across window sill, and securly closed & locked window - leaving wiffle ball on outside of window.

Only reason for the wiffle balls was to keep the shoe laces from sliding out from under the closed window should weight of cat eventually cause it to slowly slide out. My cat weighs only 9.5 pounds, so that has not yet been a problem. (has been in place for over 2 months now). What took me the longest, though, was coming up with the proper length of shoe lace/wiffle ball placement so when window is closed, the wiffle ball is snug against the outside of the window (to avoid slippage).

One other thing I did different was (after reading this on someone else's post) I reversed the position of the bolster so instead of the bolster being against the window as in the photo, the bolster is on the side of the bed away from the window since the cat is usually looking out the window & not into the room.

Overall, the product is very well made - very nice looking and sturdy. (I did have to use a hammer, though, to secure the legs (after covering that section of leg with a folded towel to prevent damage from the hammer.) Oh yeah, and the cat loves it once she figured out how to get up on it.

title: Buyers BEWARE, Read Description On Bottle Upon Arrival, Not Just Product Package!
text: I have ordered this numerous times from Chewy.com, Petco.com, and purchased in store in both petco and Petsmart, as well as from Amazon.com and never had any problems until my last 2-3 purchases of it here on Amazon. I don't know if it's a manufacturing error or something being done at Amazon directly. To my surprise though, the regular Cat Calming Diffuser Refills were shipped to me in the product packaging for the MULTICAT Diffuser Refills, rather than the Multicat refills (if that makes sense). This has now happened the last 2 or 3 orders I placed for the Multicat Diffuser refills, and I didn't bother wasting my time to return them because I was completely out of the refills when my orders arrived, and my 3 cats get very aggressive with one another if I don't have some type of the phenermone diffusers plugged in throughout my home (even after living together under the same roof the last 9-10 years :-( So I kept the orders although the wrong type of diffuser refill was inserted in the product packaging of the kind I actually needed and ordered, to try & keep the peace in my household between my 3 fur babies. But there is definitely a difference between the regular diffuser refill and the Multicat refills that my cats are use to having plugged in throughout my home, and they definitely need the multicat. I went to my local Petco and bought 6 spare of the multicat refills so that if I do decide to give it one more chance ordering from Amazon and it arrives with the wrong product in the product package again then I won't be up a creek without a paddle like i was the last few times with a household of angry kitties.....

title: Saved my dog's irritated skin
text:
I have a 5lb Papillon who started to suffer from some pretty acute dermatitis this Fall. Not sure if this was an allergic reaction to something in the grass, but she began aggressively itching her skin. I could see scabs and sores all around her ears and head, a few on the chest. I was beginning to get worried. I had tried neosporin like my vet had recommended which turned out to be the worst idea ever because it took forever to get the goo out of her hair. After trying to rinse out the neosporin, her skin was very inflamed and red and there were a lot more scabs and sores. I desperately searched on web for a cure before taking her for an emergency vet visit. I came upon this and figured I'd give it a try. WOW this is amazing.

Within 1 day of using this, I already noticed that her skin was much less red and irritated and she was beggining to stop itching. After one week, her scabs were healing and she had much fewer than before and had completely stopped itching. After two weeks, her dermatitis had completely subsided and she had no scabs, no inflammation, no itching no issues.

It's been about a month now, and she has had NO reoccurrence. Her skin is completely soothed and healthy and her coat is growing out beautifully. Thank you so much for saving us a trip to the vet and helping to restore my dog's inflamed skin. 10/10 would recommend.

title: Impressed - better than expected
text:
We were skeptical when we decided to purchase this, we currently use an Andis 60105 and had it for years, we wanted to get a quieter trimmer and one that wouldn't generate as much heat. If you had ever used a wired unit or something similar, you would realize these things run hot, burning hot, during use, it's loud and the blades and wide - for a miniature schnauzer.
We looked at several cordless units that would perform the same, the first thing was the price - so much cheaper than an Andis or simiar. To be honest, when we were ready to try, we had the Andis next to us, figuring - you get what you paid for - skeptical.
When we started.... we were WOW-ed... these are thick coats - doggos hasn't been groomed in months, knots and all. It went through with no issues, not stucked or anything. It's size is perfect to groom around the ears and between paws - couldn't do that with an Andis. It was quiet and lightweight, and being cordless, made it so much more maneuverable. The quietness was a big plus, doggos weren't shocked or shaking as they would've.
MOST IMPORTANT - Temperature, grooming one kid, takes about 30 mins on average - at least, we are by no means a pro groomer, just a home groomer for our own doggos. With the Andis, either half way through or when we are done with one, the blades and unit gets super hot and we have to take breaks in between and get creative to cool it off.
The Oneisall - we were impressed - barely any heat even when we finished the second kid and ... battery was still at 100%.
Bear in mind, this is only our first time using, and we groom every few months - hopefully it will continue it's performance for at least a few more grooms. LOVING IT

title: Gave me my life back.
text:
My parents have a senior dog they are unable to care for properly, and I was in quite a moral predicament over that situation. Instead of going through legal methods,I decided to take responsibility of the dog for the sake of the dog, which required daily or every other day visits to make sure puppy pads were always swapped out. No matter what brand or size I used it was always a disaster. And this is just a little shih-tzu over the course of a day or two! The pads would always be sopping and leaking or kicked around, I just was at my wits end and emotionally and mentally miserable trying to deal with my parents and trying to ensure the dog was taken care of hygienically. And no matter what I did or said,I couldn't make things better regarding the puppy pads.

It just felt so hopeless,because there's a solution for other similar problems, like auto-waterers,feeders,self-cleaning litterboxes,but what to do about puppy pads?
And then I learned about washable pads. And I got more excited,the more I read. I went with Rocket & Rex for the excellent reviews,even if I found the price steep,I rolled the dice on it.

I am so thankful I did. The pads held up like a champ and even though they were used,they always looked clean,they always stayed put,they didn't track or leak! And as others have put it,they washed like a dream! I added in vinegar with the laundry detergent as it said not to use bleach. Washing them twice in a row got rid of the urine smell on the heavier soaked pads,and I've had similar results with just a long soak,as well. They really did come out looking brand new and ready for action.

And I'm just so thankful. I am able to go in and check on things twice a week,allowing me some of the distance I desperately needed,while ensuring the dog always has a clean place to go. To me,it's just priceless.

title: Seems to work. Smell nice
text:
My cats, like most cats (as far as I know), don't really enjoy baths. We give them baths once a year or so, but having an alternative, like these wipes, are sure a plus. We've used some in the past, and had mixed results.

These seem to be one of the better ones. The packaging is pretty generic, and just a green package (my favorite color). Like most wipes these days, they have the plastic top you open, and then are met with a seal that you peel off. I found that a little tricky to pull off, compared to other wipes I've used, but it came off eventually. The wipes come out, nicely, and should last awhile with how they are packaged.

Now, of course, the real test was using on our cats. We received the green tea scent. I found it to be pleasant, and, as far as I know, the cats didn't mind it either. I used two wipes on each of our cats, and felt that it did a nice job of cleaning them up. Even though our cats are pretty good at grooming themselves, you know how it can be sometimes.. They step in something or somehow stink in one manner or another. These worked nicely on both cats, and they smelled just fine after. They, of course, ended up licking themselves a bit after, but I found these to do the job quite well.

title: Happy Customer
text:
Well made and easy to maneuver. Unlike toys from other manufacturers, our border collie mix can't just flip this over with her nose to retrieve her treats. This take some thinking and planning on her part. Out of the box, this has been easy to train her to use. Granted, we are only on day #2 of use, but I can tell this is quickly becoming a favorite with her and it will keep her challenged for a while. I'm impressed with the quality! This is definitely a great deal for the price.

Update 8/3/15 -
This continues to be her favorite puzzle. She's done a little chewing on the pegs during removal that make the pieces a little bumpy/sharp for human hands, but heck...this has lasted longer than any other toy she's had. In that capacity, this remains a good value and keeps her entertained.

title: Fat cat approved
text: Now, I don't like to brag but I have a BBC (big black cat). Charcoal loves to lay on boxes, bags, and in baskets of yarn. Every pizza box she has ever laid on has been crushed under her weight (when we first got her, she was a bit over weight and we have been working on getting that down). We adopted a second cat with lots of energy, so we needed something that can get Charcoal high and away, but be able to still support her. This thing has been suctioned to the window for a little over a month and has not budged, cracked, or ripped. We did move it once to her favorite spot for sunshine and people judging, so the suction power remains pretty good even after a move. Assembly was pretty easy - the hammock was slid onto the poles and not velcroed. Charcoal didn't like it at first... So we put the box it came in on top and she used it like that until she got used to the hammock. Charcoal is not a fan of soft fuzzy stuff so instead of using the fleece blanket, we added some of her favorite paper bags. All in all, best $20 I have ever spent.

title: Polydactyl Cats May Get Frustrated - Otherwise, Fantastic!
text:
My female cat Ducky loves this puzzle feeder. She took to it right away once I showed her there were yummy treats hiding among the pillars. My male cat Petrie gets a little bit frustrated with this thing because he is a polydactyl - those extra thumbs don't exactly make this activity easier! So after a few attempts at the ones that make their way to the perimeter, he will lie down and watch Ducky fish them out, soliciting for fallout.

I've noticed a positive change in my animal friends with the added mental stimulation (along with regular interactive playtime.) I would definitely recommend this feeder.

title: Relatively easy to assemble -- used for my ferret
text:
I have absolutely no tools in my house as my brother stole them. I was able to assemble this cage without any of them as the producer supplies you with the only tool you need.

So long as you follow the directions you will be good to go. I tried to skip through reading some parts and that's the only reason I had to go back a few steps a couple of times.

My main complaint is that all of the levels have wire flooring. I think that is unnecessary and does not seem enjoyable for my ferret so instead I do extra laundry in order to keep towels over the wires so she doesn't hurt her little feet. I think this is a design flaw. Also, I am a little sad that the doors aren't "doubled". Both floors only have a one-sided door, this makes cleaning her cage very hard as I have to reach around the side in order to wipe up the poop that gets stuck to the wiring.

She is an escape artist though and has not managed to slip out of this cage -- yay!

title: High Quality in a Reasonably Priced Food
text:
My dogs, a shepherd/lab mix and cattle dog mix, have done well on this food.

The maker has improved this line recently. It is on the "Approved" list for 2009 in Whole Dog Journal.

What makes it good dog food?

-No by-products, unnamed animal components, bone meal, wheat, corn, soy, sweeteners, artificial colors or flavors.
-Decent meat content. Chicken is the first ingredient, but more importantly chicken meal is the second ingredient.
-Good nutrient values: %26 protein; %4 fiber; 5:1 Omega 6 to Omega 3 fatty acid ratio. Just right for my pups.
-It is a great value.
-My dogs love it and seem to thrive on it.

I've worn myself out trying to find a very solid reasonably-priced food with a fine ingredient list that doesn't have objectionable ingredients. This one is right on the money.

title: Not appropriate for gerbils
text:
I bought this cage when I first got my gerbils, and it was terrible. Even though I had it attached to another CritterTrail cage, I later learned it wasn't enough space for both of them. They had plenty of toys to chew, but they would constantly chew on the bars (one of them broke a tooth that way), and they chewed up the Xtreme Spiral Slide in about five minutes, leaving no access to the Xtreme Wheel. The wheel got stuck after a while and wouldn't spin properly. Also, this thing is an absolute pain to clean, and the gerbils always kicked bedding out onto the floor, so I had to clean that up too.

This cage might be big enough for a single mouse or dwarf hamster, but your best bet is to get a glass or plastic tank instead. It's not as Xtreme, but it's cleaner, quieter, safer, and more fun for little pets to dig around in.

title: Good quality.
text: I was so excited to find this product in a size that would fit my small dog. I purchased this same product and brand 10 years ago for my large dog and it has held up so well! Keeps my dog safe and secure in any situation. Absolutely love that it comes in seatbelt quality material with the caribbeaner short leash. However, I was so disappointed to find that the small dog (or new?) version is not nearly as sturdy or secure. The straps do seem of decent quality but definitely much cheaper and not the seatbelt quality that is on my larger dog harness. The chest plate is nice quality and comfortable. The short leash and caribbeaner are perfect. The clasps are the biggest disappointment. I was banking on the security of the solid metal interlocking clasps for safety when riding, etc. However this harness has seemingly cheap plastic buckles that I don't think would be sufficient in an accident. Overall, a really decent harness especially for the price, but definitely a quality downgrade from expected/past experience.

title: THE ANSWER for Canine Arthritis
text:
Absolutely effective. Sucks that we have to store the big bag in the fridge, but worth it for the results. Our dog was getting bad arthritis, and limping after any kind of distance running (his favorite activity). After putting this in his food regularly for a couple weeks, the difference was night and day. No limping, no pain, and he could run with us every day like he did when he was younger. Couldn't be happier with this stuff. Oh, and he likes the taste too (but he likes the taste of everything, so that's no surprise).

UPDATE 5/3/16
About to order another big bag of this stuff. It's a miracle worker for our old guy. He just turned 10, and as long as we're putting this powder in his food regularly, he can run and play without the resulting arthritis pain. Cannot recommend this stuff enough.

title: Great Quality
text: I bought this ahead of time for the upcoming winter season so that I would have it when I need it for my senior dog.  Because I haven't tested it out in inclement weather yet, I only gave it 4 stars.  If it works out like I think it will, it will deserve 5 stars.  I ordered the 17 inch Windstorm Series in charcoal and gray.  He has a 20 inch back length and 24 inch girth.  The girth is a bit loose on him, but that's how it goes with longer bodied dogs.  However, the quality is excellent and the fill is substantial.  I am sure that it will cover him well and keep him toasty whether for a quick potty break or a short little rambling hike out in the wilds.  Beneath the coat is room for a harness.  Beneath the harness hole is fleece material between the opening and the dog.  The elastic leg straps in the rear have clips so that you don't have to pick up the dog's legs to thread them through the straps.  I like the excellent neck coverage of the detachable neck cover, the nylon lining, and the overall appearance.  I also like that it uses buckles instead of velcro.  For some reason, the charcoal/black was deeply discounted at less than $20, so I think I got a great deal.  I wish there was a size between the 17 inch and the 22 inch coats.  I really wish that Derby Originals made coats that are longer in the back and smaller in the girth for those long bodied dogs.  Their coats really are very nice quality.

title: My Bulldog Loves This!!
text: I have an English bulldog who is nine months old now and I also have a big pool. English bulldogs are notorious for being awful swimmers. Not a great mix, right? As a concerned dog owner, I scoured the internet and even spoke with my boss on multiple occassions (I work in a vet clinic) to try and find some sort of life vest for my pup. I was concerned about fit, durability, comfort, floatation, keeping her head up, and being able to lift her and guess what covers all of those bases: THIS! I took her measurements just as the picture said and purchased the Large, I believe. She was a few pounds under the recommended weight at the time but I knew she was going to gain a little more weight and bought it anyways. The fit is adjustable and leaves my pup feeling secure, the product has held up for multiple swims and continues to hold, my pup has never had an issue walking, running, swimming, or playing while wearing this lifevest, it keeps my top-heavy bully afloat, the chin part keeps her face up so she can breathe, and the double-handles makes lifting her out of the water easy and safe! Absolutely perfect! I definitely recommend this to any dog owners and especially to those with dog breeds that are known to sink!

title: really - the best
text:
Been through - literally - every type of bedding available with guinea pigs and now gerbils. This stuff is simply crinkled pieces of recycled paper, but it's awesome for a few reasons:

1. there is NO DUST, none - some brands say there isn't but there is, this is paper, there is no dust at all, ever
2. this stuff is totally absorbent, but has no smell, and allows for very little smell if you keep up on cleanings
3. it is easy to clean up. with pine I used to use a scoop, and carefresh would get clumpy. this is a breeze.
4. this stuff goes a LONG way - do not be put off bag the bag/box. Gerbils have a 40 gallon tank and even when I
create a THIN layer they move it around and "sculpt" it to their liking and it ends up being more than I needed
(i.e. those crinkles make the paper expandable, and eventually these creatues will make it expand when they dig and
move it around)
5. recycled
6. ironically, my wife has many allergies and this is the only bedding that didn't bother her (nevermind the pets)

Recommend very highly.

title: Great heater for the price!
text:
Purchased the 100w for a 20g long and it is heating the tank just fine. Old unadjustable 100w aqueon heater was only heating the tank to about 70ºF despite claims of being able to maintain temperatures of 77ºF. This heater fixed my problem and I moved said aqueon heater into a newer small tank.

My only gripe about this product is that the heating device itself is rather large. The glass tube has a wider diameter than I am used to with these types of products, and simply just takes up a lot more space in the tank than I was anticipating. Luckily, my tank is heavily planted and gave me the opportunity to hide this thing, but for other buyers thinking about purchasing this item for tanks 20 gallons or under, you may want to keep this in mind when designing your aquarium setup.

All the reviewers barking about the digital thermometer not being accurate likely never let the plastic-tipped device reader adjust long enough in their tank water. While it may take longer to adjust, it is as accurate as my mercury thermometers. I use both since the mercury thermometers are sometimes hard to read, but if both devices are reading similarly, I'm not worried.

title: Probably one of the healthiest treats available
text:
I try to avoid inexpensive / cheaply made treats for my pups. Too many chemicals out there and losing beloved furry family members to cancer is the absolute PITS. I have to say, my pups LOVE these. They certainly aren't the cheapest treat in the world, and that's why I look at these at TREATS - not snacks.

But seriously, were else are you going to find venison as the # ingredient with sweet potatos, chia seeds, flax seeds mixed with a little glucosamine and chondroitin for hips & joints. Nothing bad. AND -- sourced in the USA.

Side note BONUS: They're easy to break into small pieces for my Schipperke-Pom who does not have strong jaw power. A tad pricey, but if you're giving them as TREATS and not SNACKS, they go further - AND they are actually GOOD for your pups.

title: Chew-Zilla was denied destruction
text:
I have a year and a half old chocolate Labrador retriever, Loki, that chews and chews hard. I bought this toy because a neighbor who has a yellow lab has had the same toy for over a year. I can buy a toy and Loki will have it broken or severely damaged within minutes. It's easy to kiss 10 dollar toys good bye in less than 10 minutes.

I have had the product for about a month and it is by far Loki's favorite toy, even without treats. I have played tug of war, fetch, and other dog favorite games; the ball-like object is in perfect condition still. He will carry the toy about the house in his mouth, very regal and proud looking, as if he's King In The Castle.

Some dog toys over time will gain a very bad odor. After a month of constant use, this thing does not give off an odor that I can tell. I won't put my nose or mouth near it, but from a couple of feet away, it still seems to smell like new. If this ever gains an odor of some sort, I will probably resort to washing it and then adding some vanilla extract to the water to give it a humanly pleasant flavor. I have done this for other toys and Loki seems to have a renewed interest in them.

I have not allowed him to take the toy outside as we have several feet of snow and that would just be begging to be lost. Based on the design, this thing will be a dirt magnet on the inside, especially since my backyard is in quasi-woods with zero grass.

The treats that came with it seemed to be enjoyable for Loki. It took him about an hour and a half to eat. He didn't figure out how to pop them out as some people have stated. He just gnawed and licked it the whole time. The treats are a bit expensive, as I can buy raw hides or real bones for less.

Peanut butter is your friend. Smear some on the inside and Loki goes crazy trying to lick and clear it. You can break up dog treats or put dog food in it and it will slow them down. Loki has become an expert at getting them out, removing them in less than a minute.

With all of that said and done, I would highly recommend this treat to anyone who has a dog that can truly chew. It has held up over a month, which is very rare for a dog toy, and it has done so with not a scratch or gouge to the toy which has never been done. I put these on the same level as the dog toys from Old Navy!

I don't know what we would diabetes done without it. We adopted a cat that had ringworm and he was kind enough to share it with us. LOL. The "old fashioned" way of eliminating it worked. Of course WE didn't use it on ourselves but we bathed all the cats and the one that brought it many times. Smells terrible but it's worth it. It's not a nice smell, they'll never make candles with the scent but it is nothing compared to the results.

I have an extra bottle just in case it happens again. Oh, on Amazon you can get a fluorescent flashlight and the ringworm lights up. It was handy, though I think I'll replace my carpet. If you use it you will know what I mean. 😉

Really great for large dogs who are aggressive chewers, plus it has a squeaker!
BEWARE though, the squeaker can get pretty loud, especially when our dog is in the zone. The fact that it is beef flavored also prevents him from ever putting it down.
This is the first toy he picks up when he wants to play.
BIG thanks to the amazon exchange team and the seller for the 6 month warranty! That is a deal you cannot top.
Though the toy itself is very tough and durable, it is no match for King, our pitbull.

TIP: I wish there was a tougher version of this toy in the future.
King can easily pick it apart in a week tops.

title: Not bad, but probably better for smaller dogs.
text:
[[VIDEOID:b45080648d865e99475405c002ecabb5]] This might be better for smaller dogs. My guy eats 1 cup of food per meal and I have to fill up all the little bubbles (barns, the instructions call them) and then I fill up the four holes where the food comes out too. I'd say it's probably best for dogs who eat 1/2 a cup at a time. His food (Purina One) fits in the holes, but I also think something with smaller pieces would work better. Additionally, he's big enough to try to rip pieces off of this thing... He tried to chew on one of the doors once but didn't really try to destroy anything (though, once it was empty, I put it away immediately)
That said, this did keep him occupied for about 6 or 7 minutes, batting things around and opening the little doors. He can eat a bowl of food in about 30 seconds, so this is much better than that. It did move around WAY too much and he had trouble moving the bubbles because the whole thing scooted unless he held it down with a paw. The listing mentions rubber pads, but it's more of an adhesive, and I'm not too fond of the idea of adhering it to the floor... I wish it had a grippy rubberized or silicone finish on the bottom instead.
It's pretty easy to clean. The little bubbles can come off so you can clean them individually and get to the surface to clean the top well. Also, it comes with an extra door (probably in case a dog chews one off...)
Overall, I think this is a good product, but it could use a few improvements and is better for smaller dogs. I have a Kong Wobbler that my dog usually uses for meals, and that's probably what I'll continue to use most of the time. But, this can be fun to pull out when he needs a little challenge or to get some brain energy expended.

title: Great for introducing cats!
text:
This is a very good product! I recently took in a new cat and I’m trying to slowly introduce him to my other 2 kitties. I’m following the method recommended by Jackson Galaxy (videos are on YouTube), and now we’re to the point to where it’s time for my kitties to see each other from a safe distance. This screen is perfect for that.

I did read many reviews from other models by different sellers, and a common complaint for those was the lack of strength for the Velcro. With this model, I think the Velcro is quite strong. It bonded well to my door frame, which I did wipe down with isopropyl alcohol beforehand. Even though I do think the Velcro is quite strong, I still did reinforce mine with some nails just to be safe. For most cats, I don’t think it’s necessary to do this step. My new cat did climb to the top, so keep that in mind if your kitty is heavy. The screen is dense but definitely see-through. My new kitty can’t get through the screen to claw my other kitties.

The zipper is very good too. There are double zippers on both sides, and they work very well. You will definitely want to measure your door and make sure your purchasing the appropriate size. Mine fit my door perfectly, meaning there wasn’t wiggle room. I’m extremely pleased with this product and I really do recommend it!

title: Wanted to love it, but.....
text:
I was real excited when I bought this product. I really liked it at first, but after about 4 months of use I can see I should've went for better quality.

Complaints:
#1 It leaks. It seems to leak around the o-rings that move with the pistons to allow and stop the flow of water through the filter. They are loose or stretch and get pinched in the opening they are supposed to slide into. Thus allowing the slow leak that you see around the base of the filter. FYI: if you kind of try to "work it in" that usually works and no more leaks.
#2 The stupid yellow handle is made of thin plastic and when you turn it to open and close the valves its kind of a soft connection to the valves. It would be better if it was aluminum or whatever material is stiffer and allows full closure of the valves.
#3 Cheap clamps for the connections. Had to use automotive clams cause mine kept leaking.
#4 It leaks again! It leaked from the base of the unit. Not from the filter. This tricked me cause I thought it was my filter leaking again so I took the filter off and resolved to do fix it in the morning since it was late. When I woke up I had to figure out why my 55 gallon tank was missing 3in of water from the top.

Bottom line:
It does what it's supposed to do. When it works it works, is whisper quiet, and my water is crystal clear, but it's not worth the headache though. Buy better quality and...

DO NOT BUY THIS BRAND CANISTER FILTER!!!

title: Meat Pate' in Cardboard Container
text: There are things I like about this Honest Kitchen Meal Booster, and things I don't.  What I do like about the Honest Kitchen Meal Booster is the dogs LOVE it!  It's kind of a pate' consistency, and just meat and water! It looks a little disgusting to me, but the dogs don't care what it looks like, they just love the taste/smell.  I use it mainly for my oldies to take their meds with.  Scoop out a spoonful and hide their pills inside the meat and down the hatch they go without even a thought. I also put a small dollop on top of their kibble.  One container will last me about 2 days (4-5 meals for 2 dogs getting a couple spoonfuls per meal), and I just set it in the fridge once opened to keep it fresh.  I'm not impressed however with the cardboard packaging.  You have to get out the scissors, unfold the top, cut the top off at the dotted line, then open, and refold to seal.  It's also impossible to get all the meat out of the bottom corners of the container, unless you add some water and swish around and pour it out, and still may have some left stuck in the corners.  Overall, I'm pleased with the meal booster itself, just not the packaging.  The dogs and I give it 4 paws up.

title: It's a great size, but the wiring is rather thin and ...
text:
Unfortunately, this crate wasn't worth the money. It's a great size, but the wiring is rather thin and easily damaged. When I first received it one of the wires connected to the base came apart right away. Because it was a minor problem we decide to use it anyway and my dog loved it, but then I loaded the crate into my car for a trip and the crate somehow became bent beyond repair. Somehow the wires on the crate became twisted into each other (it's hard to explain) and now the crate can't even fold open.

Ultimately, it was okay while it lasted- but it didn't last very long. If I could do it over I would invest in a more expensive, sturdier crate of the same size.

title: Disappointed
text:
We have only had this for 4 days and our newly adopted dog has managed to unhook the piece that is supposed to hold the plastic tray in place and slide the tray out of the crate. Unfortunately for us, tonight (the second time) she unhooked it, slid the tray about 1/2 out and started lifting on it until she had it all broke up. Since we have camera on her, we saw the whole thing go down but were too far away from home to do any good. Within 15 minutes, she had the half remaining in the crate completely destroyed.

If you buy this unit, I HIGHLY recommend using something to secure the hook so it cannot be released. She did it by pressing and biting against the end of the crate until it came unhooked. If I can find a replacement tray, I plan to try zip ties. Hopefully, she won't be able to get her teeth on it well enough to break them.

title: This is not a good product for all cats!

We adopted the most affectionate shelter cat. I bought this to help him adjust to his new home. Over a three week period, he became extremely aggressive and it was beyond playing rough. We actually considered surrendering him back to the shelter, it had gotten that bad. Fortunately my husband researched and found this does encourage aggressive behavior in a very small percentage of cats.I immediately unplugged it and after 3 days our loving boy is almost back to normal.I will definitely be returning the refills I purchased! Please know we are the exception, but I wanted to let people know that it is a possibility before they give up on their fur baby,

title: A MUST for Labs!
text: These balls and the Chuckit have been a lifesaver for us. Currently, we have two Labs (3 1/2 years old and a 8 month old). These guys need exercise and they both love to play ball. Actually, they're relentless about it. They either want to eat or play ball. I'm afraid they would run till they pass out, so we have to stop playing after so many throws, because they just will not quit. A few minutes of throwing the ball as far as possible & they're satisfied for a while. The balls are tough too. They love to tear the felt off of tennis balls, so that's no good. These Chuckit balls fit the bill. Plus the glow in the dark ball is awesome. If we go somewhere during the day, getting home after dark, we use the Glow in the Dark ball (which charges up quickly with a MagLight flashlight) & can get some energy spent at night. Best is the bright orange one. I wish it was offered in a two-pack, because it's so much easier to see when the dog misses the throw & you're out walking in tall grass searching for a little ball. They're tough also. Our little one is a chewer, but hasn't chewed up one of these balls yet. We only have bought a dozen of these, because we lose them. Either they get left in the yard & found by the lawnmower, bounce into the pond, or the dog carries it off somewhere. But I make sure to always have a backup. That's how important these are to our doggie/human relationship. Definitely a must have for our Labs!

title: Comfortable and fits well. Will shred in time.
text:
This Extra Small Soft Kong recovery / "E" / Elizabethan collar fits my 10 lb cat just fine. It was easy to slip it over her head, draw the string snug (with room to slip a finger or two between the collar and her neck), and then tie a small knot to prevent the clasp from slipping.

It's been on her almost continuously for over a week. She has not been able to remove it, try as she might. She cannot lick her tail, not scratch her ears/face with this on.

The soft collar does help out when she bumps around the house, as it is not quite as jarring an experience as it would be with a stiff collar. I've kept her nails trimmed short, but still she is slowly scratching away at the fabric.

The cone has two layers of fabric, with 'boning' within to help keep it stiff. After receiving it, you will need to reshape the boning to make a good cone shape. I think the boning is very thin strips of metal.

She adapted well to it, and this is the first time she was in a collar. She can eat and drink, and seems to sleep just fine. She even jumps around, after learning that she has no peripheral vision. But I do take fragile objects down now. A note on food and water: Use a bowl that the edges curve in, or gets narrower, towards the base. Typical wide based pet bowls proved to be hard for her to eat and drink from, as the collar gets in the way. With a narrow based bowl, the collar fits under the lip of the bowl.

After about 1 week, I noticed tears in the outside fabric from her nails. It was only too soon that she would catch on one of those small tears and break through. So, I merely reversed the collar, so the outside was inside and a new fresh layer awaited her attempts.

I'm sure that by the end of the second week, she will have broken through. I've ordered a second collar to be ready when that happens.

I can't knock the product for wearing out though, as IT IS FABRIC and it WILL TEAR. I think for the price and the amount of time it lasts, it is a fair deal.

I did knock 1 star off though for the way it arrived. The cone was very misshaped and needed to be carefully reshaped. The boning is very thin, and if you are too aggressive at reshaping, it could snap.

Other than that, it is a very good product.

title: My dog's favorite Tripett product so far

text:
I have two dogs who like to dig holes in the backyard and no amount of training was changing their behavior. title: Very attractive set and a great value!
text:
I’m really happy with this collar set! See accompanying pictures for a visual reference.

The colors as I hoped match very with my pup, but the beige and subtle red and black is a great combination. The quality of the snaps and leash latch seem very solid; I especially appreciate that the leash latch opens very wide making it easier to get in the collar (in fact, you could fit it on the collar itself instead of trying to locate the d-ring .. very handy). The bow tie is a great touch, though as with my pup may be hard to see with long-haired dogs. The tie has small elastic bands for easy removal/putting on. The last nice touch is a small bell which is actually pretty loud! I took it off, though, because was freaking out my pup. I think the leather backing is maybe not as durable—I probably would rather have had just the material throughout. But it is a nice color and texture contrast.

The leash is longer than I expected and a good, useful length in my book. It’s similarly attractive and well made as the collar.

So, I absolutely do recommend giving this set a look! It’s very attractive and a great value -

title: Great Purchase, Cats Love It!
text:
I purchased this based on other comments and because it had more height than many similar products (for the price point I was looking for). When I was putting it together (wasn't more than 30 minutes), the cats weren't sure what to make of it (we have two). One immediately started scratching on the posts as was designed, but once I had it all put together, they were a bit suspicious of it. My daughter put one of the cats on it, and the surface seem to make the cat nervous initially and the cat jumped off. I then began to scratch the top post with my fingers and swat at the ball at the top. This got the cat back up on it and now she perches on the top, napping and playing with the ball. Our other cat is a bit of a fatty, but she works her way to the top as well (but I haven't seen her on the very top piece, but she swats aggressively at the ball hanging from it and she loves scratching the posts all over it.

The product seems strong/sturdy. Nothing wobbles (despite sitting on a carpeted floor) and I don't see it shake when the cats jump up and down on it.

text: The size of this cage is more than I anticipated, it's amazingly large! It has a lot of nice features as well, although not all of them work out too well. Our youngest guinea pig learned to use the ramp within the first 24 hrs and LOVES running (yes, running) up and down it. However, our older guinea pig (who's about a year old) has still not learned how to use the ramp and it has been about a month now. The green hide-away/food access platform keeps getting peed on, which is pretty awful. We ended up removing it and putting a hammock there instead. Also, the hole which the ramp is attached to causes much of the litter to fall into the lower cage, and within a week, the upper cage is almost without litter, We are making our own modification to resolve this. We bought pvc baseboard pieces and are going to make edging around the hole to help hold the litter back so it doesn't fall through. Overall, it needs these modifications! But for the size of the cage, and the price, I still don't regret it.

title: I Love It, The Cat Wants to Suplex It
text:
Short Version:
It works, and most importantly it survives constant abuse.
Some mods/improvements could be had though imho.

Long Version:
I have a calico that was terribly overfed by my prior roommates that I have the pleasure of dieting now that we're living solo. Portioning & Scheduling worked, but I was tired of being woken up 15min before my first alarm every day, as well as surviving the regularly scheduled "Diet Riots" from my not-so-tiny monster.

Enter the Ymiko Automatic Feeder.

Pros:
- I am no longer the food dispenser, so I can sleep peacefully... to a point.
- Unlike people, the feeder cannot be bullied into extra pity servings. It is cold, heartless, and gives a calculated feeding at a precise time. This also means I can enjoy life outside without worrying about Ms Kitty's schedule.
- My god is it RESILIENT. I have seen this thing get thrown to the side, slammed against the wall for hours on end, and outright abused for the last 2 months by a very hangry calico cat. But it does not open up, and even on it's side it will only spit out the calculated portion at the calculated time.

Cons:
- Unfortunately, kitty has learned she can reach her arm up the chute and rattle around for a chance at an extra1-2 pieces of kibble. She gets maybe 1 extra kibble per day, but all its done it reinforce her that there's a CHANCE. If she is anything, she is persistent. A little one-way door would solve this, so some kitchen-engineering is in the works to create a fix.

- The bowl is easily detached from the feeder during it's frequent boxing matches. I know this is for easy cleaning but I almost wish it was permanently attached, or made from a heavier material. I also wish said bowl had some kind of felt/rubber feet, because the sound of plastic scraping over vinyl flooring is just awful. A hand towel under the feeder is the easiest fix I've found.

- It is a lightweight machine that is (somehow) surviving each day with a 16lb calico that wants nothing more than to see this thing destroyed. I wish it had a heavier base to help keep it from being rocked about so easily. While I am not being pestered at 5:45am, I can still hear the poor feeder being slammed against the wall at 6:03am every day when kitty attempts to bully more food from it. If a 5lb weight can't fix this, my next step is to secure it to a table leg so it cannot be moved by man or beast.

title: Great tool (just be very careful!)
text: Oh man this worked incredibly well for my old dog. He is 16 years old and it's too risky to put him under for teeth cleaning. I'm embarrassed to say that the plaque on his teeth was horrifyingly awful. Brushing wasn't going to cut it. I got an LED reading light pointed on his teeth, made him comfortable laying in my lap on an old towel, wore gloves, and was VERY VERY VERY VERY slow and careful. You canNOT get in a hurry or you WILL hurt your pet or yourself.  Sloooow and controlled work. It took me at least a couple hours plus to get all his teeth cleaned. They look SO much better and I'm sure he feels so much better. I know I sure feel better knowing his teeth are clean! (His bad breath is gone, too, of course ;)  If you have the choice please take your animal to a professional to have their teeth cleaned. I just cannot risk exposing him to that environment at this old age. So NOW, that I have the proper tool, I can do maintenance upkeep. :)

We purchased this cover to keep dirt, dust, mud, and moisture off the back seat. It fits our 2019 Subaru Forester perfectly! I can still use the safety belt that attaches to the car seat anchor and her harness to keep her safe while riding in the back seat, which is a priority for us.

The fabric seems durable and easy to clean, and doesn't have that petroleum smell that some waterproof covers seem to have. In short, we are very happy with this product.

title: My senior westie can run up the slope now!
text:
This supplement really helps with my senior dog, a 10.5 year old westie. I started looking for a glucosamine supplement when my westie turned 9 and had difficulty walking up the slopes during our walks and needed more tries to jump up the couch. A close friend of mine with 3 dogs recommended this so I decided to give this a try.

I thought the Beef liver flavor would make this supplement more palatable for my westie but I guess it wasn't enough as it smelled more medicinal than anything as he wouldn't eat it. I decided I would turn this into a powder form using my food processor and sprinkle over his kibbles. To mask the medicinal smell, I would mix a tiny amount of the supplement powder with a tsp of coconut oil, followed by his kibbles and serve. It worked! He ate it up right away since he loves coconut oil. I gradually increase the supplement over time so that he would get used to the taste of this new supplement and he has been doing much better ever since. He would even run up the slope now at 10.5 years old.

I saw some reviewers mentioned that their dog wouldn't eat this supplement and thought I could share what I did to get my dog to eat it and experience the health benefits this supplement provide.

FYI, I kept the powder form of the supplement in a dark and cool place and it didn't clump or go bad.
